An index finger longer than the cancelation indicates a lower risk of cancer
The men have the highest rate that cancel are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a studied published Wednesday in the British journal of cancer.
Could they depend on the level of male hormone testosterone.
"Our results indicate that the length of the finger on can be a test of the risk of prostate cancer, in particular for men aged up to 60 years," said the co-author of the study Professor Ros eeles, of the Institute for cancer research at the University of WARWICK.
Consequently, the finger could help predict which men should undergo a test for prostate cancer, particularly if this characteristic is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as health problems, according to family indicates eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, provided the review with a British counterpart of more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the índica finger of the right hand more quickly than the override.
They just as likely to suffer prostate cancer that 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with longer than the finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men aged less than 60% reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the width of two fingers in question, in the prenatal period, reflecting different levels of the hormones for which it is exposed foetuses in the womb.
A lower level of testosterone corresponds with longer.
Previous studies suggested that testosterone can influence the development of prostate cancer.
The great genetista Czech, and former President of the National Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav pačes, said at the same time that you are familiar with the study, but it seems that the relationship between the length of the fingers and the cancer can "prove completely."
