At every turn failure a cabezal, does akpobari, then there is a constant pinch of oil in the water.
According to assessments of the experts, have been made more than two billion litres in 50 years in the Delta ecosystem: year after year, the amount of oil it runs, as in the averia vessel 'Exxon Valdez' 21 years ago in the sea of Alaska, one of the largest ecólogicas disasters in the history of humanity.
Who is responsible for the lasting environmental region, lidiará with it.
While the consortium of Shell and the organised theft of oil are responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution, environmentalists view the warheads into low-enriched to break point and the pipes with losses as the main source.
In Nigeria, Shell applies mainly low safety standards normally in the conventional world, liberate the scientist Richard Steiner to the consortium in 2008: only the defects of the pipes are "on a multiple higher than elsewhere."
In a place far away seems forgotten, appears a garage full of oil under the open sky, winged between mangrove forests are: naked and covered in oil.
Between one of the many barrels, which are sometimes attached to drilling, sometimes arbitrarily scattered on the ground, flamea a fire: a small illegal refinery.
In the barrel, oil is hot in the fire more hours, explains Michael, the head of the group.
Firstly, the petrol runs through the pipes in the shaft, later the pipeline of leaking oil and diesel finalemente goes.
In this way, Michael and four employees produce daily until four barrels of diesel 300 litres: "give us 34 naira," around $22.
The inhabitants of the Delta advantage the fuel shortages in one of the biggest oil states of sub-Saharan Africa.
Nigeria has only a single refineria.
With the cheap price of diesel and only 40 euros-céntimo per litre illegal heaters can offer even less: reduce the value of its raw materials.
It stems from "the bunkers," which trucaron the network of pipes that crosses Ogoniland: according to the experts, this step will lose at least 16 million litres of oil a day in the Niger Delta.
Only a negligible part of the interim bonus material stored it refines clearly illegally: organised criminal networks, which are also political and military, remain the best hand in aljibes and sell it in the world market.
The activist akpobari considered purely academic debate over whether the environmental catastrophe is due more to the handling of the people or the poor way of production.
"If oil companies are not behaving as invaders and not have destroyed completely natural habitat for fish, would not have sabotage or theft, or refinerias illegal."
