The democratic routine
Continue to increase support for democracy in Latin America, as well as the backing for private companies.
Crime generates greater concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, he sees Brazil as a country more influential than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest survey of latinobarómetro made in 18 countries and published exclusively by the economist.
Given that the survey has been taken regularly since 1995, makes it possible to carry out a follow-up to the changes in attitudes in the region.
In the results of the survey this year, conducted in September and early October, highlights two issues.
The first is the relatively vibrant mood prevailing in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes toward democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has risen considerably in various countries of the Pacific coast of South America look (table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has risen since a fallen 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Grew up in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a huge decline in output last year.
However, only half of those polled in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries are in the area, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (consult the graph 2).
About 44% of respondents in the region is extremely satisfied with the way democracy functions in practice in his country, the same figure as last year, but significantly higher than the 25% recorded in 2001 graph (3).
Around 34% said that they trusted Congress of his country and 45% in his government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher in relation to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America have seriously affected the support for democracy.
The fact that it has continued during the global financial crisis probably stems from the fact that many Latin American countries only were affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Furthermore, the existence of a network of social security more strong has helped to protect the poorest.
(the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only marginally in 2009 and that has been reduced again this year, up 32%.)
However, the mood varies considerably from one country to another (consult the graph 4).
The good economic returns of Brazil and the popularity of the outgoing President, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
That sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, most respondents in Latin America about the crime, instead of unemployment, as the most serious problem facing the country (consult the graph 5).
Around 31% say that either they or a close relative, has been a victim of crime in the last year, a figure that has been reduced from 38% last year, and that is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic returns is reflected in increased support for private companies and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say that private companies are indispensable to the development, while in 2007 was only 56% (consult the graph 6).
About 58% agrees that the market economy is the only system that will allow his country develops, compared to 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and the 80% supports private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exerts greater leadership in the region, as the 19% of respondents (compared with 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is the most influential country deemed by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds that title in the Dominican Republic, Ecuador and Nicaragua.
Elections to the rubbish
