Some of them, in the end, they gave up.
A dozen candidates for the presidential, including several of the more popular, denounced fraud and called for the annulment of the election.
The protests, some of them violent, spread across the country.
However, Edmond mulet, the senior United Nations official in Haiti, declared that the elections were "relatively good in many ways."
The observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, said cautiously that "we do not believe that these irregularities, however serious, revoke necessarily the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which according to its rivals is committed to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing President, and with their candidate, jude célestin, should announce preliminary results on 7 December.
It is predicted that the desempate will convene in January.
We do not yet have lost all hope in connection with the elections.
The two main opposition candidates, Michel martelly, a rapero, and mirlande manigat, a former first lady, have withdrawn their initial request in calling for the cancellation of the vote.
But they can still cause problems if the electoral authority states that Mr célestin, that has little or no support, has moved to the second round.
Bearing in mind that the cholera epidemic in the country and more than a million survivors of the earthquake is still living in tents, is expected to be a low voter turnout.
By the time, many Haitians wanted to vote, but they failed to do so due to a lack of organisation.
Around 250,000 identity cards needed to vote still had not been distributed shortly before the election.
There is much at stake.
Aid donors see that the choice of a popular government and legitimate is an essential step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And, as has become evident, I think the Haitians themselves.
Moving tiptoeing towards the centre
In the weeks that have passed since she lost her husband, Cristina Fernández, the President of Argentina, has enjoyed a great sympathy among the public that has grown its ratings by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level recorded since his election in 2007.
Despite everything, we can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in elections next year will depend on whether the clearly affected Ms Fernández leaves aside the intransigence of her late husband, his predecessor and political partner, Nestor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are not conclusive.
Mr Kirchner, continued to take responsibility for economic policy even after his wife version of him as president, had the habit of set budgets that infravaloraban tax revenue, the economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple spend extra revenue at their discretion.
In theory, the government of Mrs Fernandez lost their majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened following the death of Kirchner because of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some dissenting Member of the Peronist movement in power have faced Ms Fernández.
However, after a chaotic session in which a Member gave her fist to another in the face and other Members accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the budget by 2011.
"I am not going to discuss," said the President.
The 2010 budget, therefore, apply to next year, which will offer the President a margin of still greater in the spending thereof.
The economy is improving considerably: will probably grow up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, but many private calculations, in addition to the pay demands of the unions, situated close to 30%.
Mr Kirchner, who took power in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, meant that the growth and poverty reduction their priorities, instead of controlling inflation.
Refused to negotiate with the IMF, pressed the private sector and made the indec, the Institute of statistics, adaptase official statistics of inflation.
Moderará is now the President Fernández these policies?
He has convened meetings between the private sector and the leaders of the unions.
In addition, his officials say that they want to limit pay increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been fueled by high prices for Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the boost to growth achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for the very reason Ms Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore the financial ties of Argentina with the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused to advance a forced restructuring of the debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it appears that Ms Fernández is on the verge of concluding an agreement with creditor governments grouped together in the Paris Club, which has around 6.7 million dollars.
The Kirchner always insisted that this does not imply the supervision of the IMF, as usual.
However, last month, Amado boudou, the economy minister, announced that the Fund will provide "technical assistance" to develop a new consumer price index, which seems to be the prelude to the niceties of the indec.
It is not clear whether the President Fernandez is to remain in politics when his mandate, bearing in mind that no longer has to her husband at her side.
If it does, will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has tired of kirchnerismo.
When Argentines returning from their summer break in March, the wave of sympathy for she will have lapsed.
If it wants to win another election, will have to decide whether or not react, quietly, many of the policies of her husband.
Medium hurrah China
Voters in Taiwan are approaching slowly to a kind of Union closer to the mainland.
What does Taiwan on its big brother on the other side of the Strait?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70% of the eligible, went on 27 November to elect mayors and councillors of five urban districts in what appears to be a comprehensive assessment of the President, Ma Ying-jeou.
The same Mr Ma has become an advocate of sentiment on the continent, innovative forging business links, including a partial free trade pact, the biggest change in relations with China since 1949.
Mr Ma passed the test, but by a narrow margin.
Although his party Kuomintang (KMT) ended up winning three of the five elections for mayor, failed to get the most votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which has been tipped for a full independence for Taiwan, won almost 50% of all the votes compared to 45% for the KMT.
If they had been the presidential, Mr Ma would be in trouble.
Since his election two years ago, the proportion of votes of his party has fallen by almost 8%.
For the first time, the DPP empató with the KMT in Councils.
In the elections could see the typical elements of the Taiwanese elections, including noisy trucks and large crowds with banderitas and girls clothing light dancing.
It lacked the mysterious assassination attempt.
Sean LIEN, the son of Lien Chan, Honorary President of the KMT, was campaigning for one of the candidates of the KMT the night before the election.
A man in the crowd shot at young directly in the face, hiriéndole and killing a transeúnte.
The funny thing is that it has not been possible to determine if the man was inflicting harm to LIEN or take revenge on the candidate.
In any case, said tsai ing-wen, the DPP leader, the fire overran the elections, growing suspicions about the DPP and scaring voters inclinasen by the KMT.
Perhaps the only big winner of the campaign was China.
It was surprising that are not addressed the issue of the continent itself.
Instead, the candidates were told of plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan normally enjoys its de facto independence and loathes the military threat from China.
Consequently, the KMT usually avoid publicise their links with the government in Beijing.
But this time the DPP avoided encourage the feeling against China.
It responds to the awareness that the Chinese trade is essential to the economic survival of Taiwan.
For his part, Mr Ma said that it had confirmed that its policy with regard to China was acceptable to the majority of the Taiwanese.
It is envisaged that the Beijing Government is sobornándoles with trade, in accordance with its strategy to bring Taiwan back to the fold.
China lost no time sending a negotiator to Taipei to prepare for a summit on the protection of investments and the medical cooperation.
Certainly, it would also ensure the political integration, but the first thing is the first thing.
The best will be waiting for the 2012 presidential election.
In any case, the DPP has reinvented itself.
Two years ago was in a bad situation: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was jailed on charges of corruption.
President between 2000 and 2008, instigaba openly independence.
However, under the leadership of Mrs tsai, has emerged a new generation of moderates and the DPP is struggling to attract professionals and young people.
Ms tsai has been welcomed warmly welcome as DPP candidate for the Presidency, like his tseng-chang, which fulfilled mandate under Chen.
Now his party is doing everything possible to show that they can have relations with Beijing.
Ms tsai announced plans to create a group of experts that will act as an interface between the DPP and China, as long as they can take out the negotiations without preconditions.
Ms tsai says the Taiwanese public that his party is a "reliable alternative" to the hurried approach of Mr Ma with regard to China.
Mr Chen is outraged by the change.
In a statement issued from his cell, said that the DPP candidate would have been better off if they had insisted that Taiwan is an independent country.
Even ordered Mr his, a pragmatic, not the President.
Even without to Mr Chen, the DPP will have difficulty choosing between their potential candidates.
The KMT also has some soul-searching.
The assessment made by Mr Ma have been poor, despite the impressive economic growth; the KMT candidates not to campaign with him.
His unpopularity is apparently mainly due to unemployment and the growing gap between rich and poor.
A spokesperson for the KMT says it restructures his cabinet, as well as the local teams.
The bites of the DPP suggest that support for Taiwan to a rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, the majority of the Taiwanese believe that economic integration with China is inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a well-known columnist, "has already been crossed the point of no return."
