A microbe resistant to arsenic raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth or in other places...
The discovery of a strange bacteria that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients holds out the prospect of finding new ways of life on earth and, possibly, on other planets.
Although the researchers found the odd bacterium here on earth, say that shows that it is possible that there are ways of life without the main elements they saw as essential.
"This organism has a dual capacity."
"It can grow with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"This makes it into something very peculiar, although he needed to be a kind of living really 'alien'," said Paul C. W. Davies of the Arizona State University, a co-author of the report that appears in the online edition of the journal Science Thursday.
For a long time, there are six large essentials in life: carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorous and sulphur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria, found in monkey lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorous by arsenic.
"You just plantearte what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, a co-author of the report.
According to indicated Anbar, the finding is important in the search for life on other planets in the earth, given that researchers need to be able to identify the life, knowing the aspect which has.
The study focuses on a microbe found on earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which it were made public details of the discovery, led to much speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report show the discovery of life extraterrestre.
We did not.
What the discovery "shows up is that in other settings worldwide, could have bodies to use other elements to boost their biochemistry and the set of" standard "that we consider essential for life is not perhaps so flat," said Charles cockell, professor of planetary and space sciences research institute, the open university in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell not formed part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the replacement of an element for another in biochemistry and structure basic biochemistry," added cockell.
The discovery was made by chance.
Felisa wolfe-simon of the Institute of astrobiología of NASA, who led the study, focused on the monkey Lake because it contains high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar in terms of the chemical, which speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one for another.
"The arsenic is a toxic chemical mainly because their behaviour is similar to that of phosphorus."
"as a result, may find it difficult to them differentiated."
"however, arsenic is sufficiently different to that does not work as well as phosphorus, by what comes in and, as it were, apelmaza biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
The researchers also collected bacteria known as gfaj-1 and exposed the growing concentrations of arsenic, which managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbe grows best with phosphorus, but the fact that you can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that might exist naturally a way of life to use arsenic, either in other areas of the earth and another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that we can replace the arsenic for phosphorus is not new, but never found an example that should prove that it works.
Arsenic was more common in earlier eras of the land, he said, by what the researchers speculated that the first forms of life may have used.
"It suggests that there might be other means of generating life, not only how life formed on earth it used to," said foster, who was not part of the research team of wolfe-simon.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
