The lion is ready to rugir again, while the restructuring of GMMs gets the final approval of the Court
After 18 months of confusion and uncertainty, GMMs has finally got the green light to begin again.
On Thursday, a federal bankruptcy judge in New York formally approved the plan "prearmado" by creditors to wipe out about $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the entertainment of 86 years focus their efforts on the production and release of films and television programmes.
The ruling Thursday confirms that the plan meets the demands of the US bankruptcy code, so that there are no legal obstacles to GMMs revival under the founders of spyglass entertainment, Gary Barber and Roger birnbaum, who will become the top executives of what will be a small study.
The staff is reduced to approximately 320 Members.
In fact, GMMs would not emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan chase closure a credit instrument planned 500 million dollars, to fund operations and production in the new GMMs.
The investment bank is currently sindicando credit, which on its own is contributing $75 million, and is expected to be funded in mid-December.
The process of restructuring the study began in May 2009, when the investment bank moelis and Co. was contracted to give advice on the management needed to clean up their finances, as they strove to make interest payments by $300 million a year.
In the month of August, the chief executive Harry sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former President of Enron and an expert in recovery of bankrupt companies, known for his work in krispy kreme doughnuts.
The attempts of moelis and Cooper to resolve the financial travails of GMMs and satisfy the more than 140 creditors in the study, required much more time than expected.
After several months of discussions, at the end of 2009, the parties agreed to put the company on the sale.
However, the auction attracted few postores and none willing to pay more than $2 billion sought by the creditors.
Before the spring of this year, he returned to the table when the design team of GMMs began work on a restructuring plan that, after months of debate and internal disagreements, was eventually backed by creditors at the end of October.
When GMMs officially out of bankruptcy in the coming weeks, the companies of moelis and Cooper will receive multimillion bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
The companies of Cooper, who has been garnering $375 000 per month for his services from the company, will receive a "success fee" of $4 million.
Barber and birnbaum plan to resume production in GMMs, which lends only one movie this year, and annual meeting a slate of seven or eight films coming out in 2012.
Also plan to co-finance two films based on "the hobbit," along with Warner bros.
The study needs to strike a separate loan of between 265 and $275 million to fund its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
