Prosecutors kept no charges against the senator Ensign
The lawyers of Senator announced on Wednesday that prosecutors from the Department of Justice have exculpado Senator John Ensign of the criminal charges arising from his affair with a former campaign aide and its efforts to ensure work through lobby to the husband of the woman.
The decision ends the legal threat more serious facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was regarded as a potential Republican presidential candidate for 2012, so that the scandal over his affair had national headlines last year and bruised his career.
The office of Ensign said she was "certainly pleased" by the decision, which came after an investigation of a whole year.
The Senator could still face a disciplinary action by the Senate ethics committee.
The lawyers of Ensign said that the Department of Justice had "reported that Senator Ensign is no longer an objective of its research and has no plan to lift charges against him on this issue."
The Department of Justice declined to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, which said that seemed to have significant evidence to indicate that Ensign may have confabulado for violating a ban on lobbying Federal Criminal.
The interviews, e-mail and other documents that were made public in the first place in October 2009 in the New York Times noted that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative work through lobby to ensure the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the affair of the senator with her.
Ms Hampton once worked as treasurer of a campaign of Ensign.
Ensign was in contact with several sponsors politicians to find work to Mr Hampton and advocated on behalf of them after they had hired Mr Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
Like Hampton had recently been a qualified Ensign, was excluded according to the law to lobby for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said that the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were friends before the intimate affair, appeared at odds with the so-called "revolving Dorr lobbying ban," which seeks to restrict that former state employees to use their connections for personal business.
The evidence that has been made public, "appeared to be a prima facie case of conspiracy to violate the Statute substantially revolving Dorr," said Stanley Brandt, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients being investigated by the government.
While officials of the Department of Justice refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the case Ensign, Mr Brandt and other lawyers of ethics said the department seemed wary about accepting political prosecutions after several setbacks in its public integrity section, including the decision last year to abandon the prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, amid charges of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors are "clearly a cowards," said Melanie sloan, executive director of citizens for responsibility and ethics in Washington, a group that brought a number of complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the law does not apply to them," he added.
Paul coggins, the chief lawyer of Ensign, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor for the justice department on Monday and another more calls the next day, saying that the department did not want to lift charges against his client.
The defence team of Ensign had been cooperating with prosecutors in the attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments that he gave prosecutors.
"I do not feel comfortable going into detail about my discussions with the Department of Justice, I can only say that we took the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation in a separate complaint by the Group on ethics, which argues that a payment of $96,000 to the parents of Ensign to the Hampton violated federal election law.
The electoral Commission said that she did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was not more than a gift.
NV energy is a major company of Nevada, who had supported for a long time senator, which managed to work through lobby, thanks to the help that Ensign given Hampton.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that after the company agreed to Hampton as industry lobbyist, the chief of staff, John Lopez, Ensign was with Hampton and told that he was "pound" the Interior Ministry on a point of contention.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another client of Nevada, and allegiant air, called the Secretary of transportation to establish a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When we first saw the news of the affair last year, Ensign asked forgiveness from his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth leading Republican in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told journalists who planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When the speaker of Ensign, Jennifer Cooper, Ensign announced that it was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, said that the senator had expected that the ethics committee followed the example of the Department of Justice and finish his research.
"Senator Ensign wishes to continue with this difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada," he said.
The appeal of Cheshire aimed at Twitter
There were half a dozen of them, "chateando" in the ranks of the courtroom.
Minute by minute, sent reports of shocking testimony via Twitter.
In the end, says the defence, had more than 140,000 messages on Twitter on the process that went into the breach and children tied to their beds in a House which was once kindled fire.
On Thursday, the process widely followed by Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a family of Cheshire, Connecticut, is ready to come to an end, with the imposition of the judge of the death sentence passed by the jury.
But lawyers for Mr Hayes have written in court that they delineate them the arguments of appeals that probably will take to the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims that the intensive reports on the process, including the wide use of Twitter by journalists of mass media, created "a circus atmosphere," and such a glut and with details exaltadores made public passions ejercieran an inappropriate influence over the jury.
The call might force the appeal judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
"according to what I experienced during this process, I think that there is a real danger that the inclusion of the new technology in the courtroom is affecting the rights of the individual to get a fair hearing," said Thomas J. Ullmann, chief counsel for the defence of Mr Hayes.
The judge of first instance Jon C. blue, the State Supreme Court, rejected lacónicamente claims in a ruling last week, saying that news media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury has been driven by passion.
But probably will not be the last word on the subject.
For decades, the courts of appeal have acknowledged that the coverage of cases celebres may lead to questions about the fairness of the process.
In a landmark ruling in 1966, the United States Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a osteopaths of Cleveland, Dr Sam sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in its decision, in the case sheppard vs. Maxwell, who had "a carnival atmosphere in the process" due to the media.
It is believed that the crime had been inspired by the television show and the movie "the fugitive."
Some lawyers said the courts of appeals that examined the condemnation of Mr Hayes half a century later, could be intrigued by the argument that could be needed new rules to control the form of communication from the halls of the Court, something inimaginadable in the case of Dr. sheppard.
"There is a reason for concern about the impact of the new media" in processes of high profile, said John J. donohue III, a professor at Stanford law school, who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report which said it was imposed arbitrarily.
Professor donohue said that some judges of appeal could be intrigued by the idea that limit the immediate communication from the halls of the Court could make that trials were fair.
The issue of Twitter is just one of many of the issues outlined by lawyers from Hayes, which will probably be discussed for years, delaying the execution.
The defence lawyers also say, for example, that Hayes could have been undermined when the judge blue refusal to allow testearan reactions of potential juries by showing gruesome photos of the scene of the crime during the selection of the jury.
Some juries have said that they were shocked by the pictures of the victims, Jennifer hawke-petit, 48 years, and their daughters, hayley, 17, and michaela of 11.
The defence lawyers say that also take the constitutionality of the death penalty and will argue that the judge incorrectly removió to a jury that had criticized prosecutors, and that incorrectly had lobbied for a verdict by the bizarre decision to it be possible to tell the jury deliberate over a weekend.
The panels were not abducted.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense coverage of the process may attract the most interest.
They noted in a challenge to the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the United States Senate.
They argued that the media constantly meant grist to the mills of the excitement about the case.
"The crowding of tweets from the media, the cameras and reporters outside the court," wrote the attorneys, "was something not seen here in new haven and perhaps throughout the state."
His attention in the coverage of tweeter is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said that the complaint about the fact that the immediate news were more important than the reports delivered more slowly, were a ludita vision that would make the politics of the Court on the control of the coverage was weak in future.
But some lawyers said the courts of appeal often were swayed by the arguments on the adjustment required in the courts because of technological and social changes.
The lawyers of Hayes are pushing for this call.
In his letter, mentioned the 1966 decision of the Supreme Court, repealing the condemnation of Dr. sheppard due to coverage of the process, and made it clear that would require new media would require new rules.
"this case," wrote, "represents the case sheppard vs. Maxwell of the 21st century."
Can the civility bridge to link the divisions?
After a campaign marked by the tirade and the negativity, this week has sparked a bit of civility in Washington.
Is it a harbinger of a genuine bipartisan cooperation future or a delusional before a rapid return to the fray party in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and Congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on major issues that must be handled during the lame-duck session.
But according to everyone, was at least a polite discussion of the difference of the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, instead of being another episode vacuum for partisan gain.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the Commission 's deficit President was equally civilized, despite political differences that exist between Members.
It seems clear that the close interaction during a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates the Members.
That is hardly enough to declare that it has reached a new era of cooperation.
Now both sides are in a trial period, sondeándose each other to identify signs of cooperativismo and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and patience from voters to a renewed war.
Which is why the meeting on Tuesday and the subsequent evaluations of the same by the participants took control with a minimum requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and they are very deeply ingrained as to suggest any rapid change of climate that existed during the past two years.
Whether it is tax, spending, health care or social support, the two parties are poles apart.
Anyway, the election of November has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in relation to the way of saying things," said pete wehner, a Bush administration official now at the center for ethics and public policy.
"are inevitable after the election.
The elections give partisan passions, which are dying out.
That is a good thing ."
On some issues, particularly those mentioned in the order of the day of the lame-duck session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
The Bush tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, it is likely to be a commitment to extend the unemployment, probably because the Republicans can not believe that they are in favour of the tax cuts for the rich, denied unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After the meeting on Tuesday in the White House, there is greater optimism about a possible deal on these issues during the lame-duck session, along with the ratification of the new deal on nuclear disarmament start (strategic arms reduction treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution, notes that the successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the lame-duck session does not necessarily lead to a continuous bipartisanship when the new 112do. Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, it is highly likely and inevitable, begins a period of disagreement.
"after that things that are due to be carried out, in the short term, psychology reverse the situation to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) on the fact that the citizen can lead to a real partnership.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a test for the main event in 2012," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the Constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who were instrumental in its creation.
For more awareness with Republican leaders about the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know that they must try to fulfill his promises to cut the cost of the state and the new law.
These partisan lines are already clearly in initial reactions against the recommendations of the Committee on the deficit, including the reform of the tax code and increasing some taxes and retirement age, and the retrenchment.
The Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and erskine Bowles have been responsible for one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, according to its own valuation, have introduced to force the issue of the deficit in the order of the day in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the Committee on 18 Members to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been fighting to get close to that figure.
The strongest resistance is between the elected officials in the panel, suggesting that in tax-related issues, at least today, few bases or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two stages in the battles between Republicans in the White House and the Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of clashes supporters, when the Republican challenge to Obama over the budget, taxes and health care, followed then by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties to work together.
If the confrontation leads to a standstill, as happened in 1995, then both parties will be watching the reaction of the people.
Anyone who feel that it is losing probably will change course and seek compromise.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
The partisanship and the polarisation are now higher than they were in the 1990s, and seems to have a bigger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress who had between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the prelude to a more momentous in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilismo showing this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on the part of both sides to find commonalities in the issues that still divide them.
A US document leaked portrays to Moscow as paradise of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "kleptocracy," and leaves a part of the bribes and money that collects directly to the Kremlin, as reported in February, the US Embassy in Russia.
It reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service manage huge systems of blackmail, which helps to explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They collect money not just of legitimate businesses, but also of organised crime groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy, which Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has termed the "top-down authority," takes his hand as the money to get on the scale.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks in its Web site Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while he was still mayor, Yuri Luzhkov, Moscow, and blame him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a clean sweep since then.
Luzhkov, and his wife, Yelena baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied the allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several demands for libel over the accusations.
In September, when in a Russian television channel asked about a documentary that suggested that he was corrupt, said: "This is madness, a canard, a nuisance."
According to surveys, the Russians believe overwhelmingly that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explicados closely, as they were in the report of the embassy, and it is extraordinary that the diplomats of a foreign country who do that.
"The direct links to the government of the city of Moscow with crime, have led some to call it 'dysfunctional', and to say that the government operates more like a kleptocracy that as a government," says the note.
"The criminal elements have 'krysha' (a term of the criminal world and of the mafia, which literally means" roof "or protection) which transcends the police, the Federal Security Service (sfs), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the office of the prosecutor, as well as all sectors of the bureaucracy of the government of the city of Moscow.
"analysts identified a structure of three levels in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The sfs, MVD and militia are on the second level."
"Finally, the common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is a system ineffective in which criminal groups fill a vacuum in some areas, because the city does not provide certain services."
The report says that the sfs collects the money from the larger companies, and that the police showed small shops.
A source, said the report, "explained that the Moscow business owners understand that the best is to ensure the protection of the MVD and sfs (instead of the groups organised crime) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power that criminal groups, but are also protected by the law."
"for this reason, the protection against criminal gangs is no more a priority."
The document notes that, while the tax money is complete, protection can be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay are quickly closed their businesses as a pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has achieved little progress.
The note to the embassy report men taking, probably suitcases full of cash, within the same Kremlin.
"in its fight against corruption, Medvedev has to rely on the bureaucrats," said Georgy satarov, director of the group of experts from indem in Moscow, in a recent interview.
"but he is a part of this tape."
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, indem estimates that corruption costs to Russia more than $300 billion per year.
In a recent survey on global perceptions of corruption carried out by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was classified at 154 (the countries are classified in the least to most corrupt).
The disclosure of the document of the American embassy, which did not occur until late at night in Moscow, surely will cause anger within the Russian Government, and despite that Luzhkov can be blamed for the weaknesses of Moscow, could be an opportunity to claim that the Kremlin is solving the problem.
Interviewed for the CNN for Larry King, Putin suggested that the documents WikiLeaks might be lies and reacted furiosamente by revealing that said that American diplomats called Batman and Robin to Medvedev.
"The truth of the matter is that this concerns our interaction, which is an important factor in the domestic policies in this country," she said.
"But to be honest with you, not we suspect that this would be done with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, that was done in a manner so immoral."
Veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to confront the past
In a particular classroom weakly lighted, with stained walls and descascaradas, the director of the school anlong veng recalled the man who had constructed, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"everyone here love Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and was preoccupied by his people," said sreng KOR Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" by its brutality during the Khmer Rouge commander, remains popular in this remote former fortress of the Khmer Rouge in north-west Cambodia, where built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where still live thousands of former soldiers of the organization.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge is account with the government, the loyalty continued for a long time is being finally challenged in anlong veng.
In April, a local forum for the truth and reconciliation allowed victims who were publicly to people who had taken part in the scheme.
In June, the government distributed a textbook of secondary school for the first time taught the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint court of the United Nations and Cambodia issued the first conviction of a former Member of the Khmer Rouge, the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing khek iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each one of these events, the anxiety has grown among veterans of the Khmer Rouge in anlong veng, complicating the efforts for reconciliation and his attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge, but they cannot do anything," said youk chhang, director of the documentation centre of Cambodia, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"for them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"This is creating divisions within the families."
During the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia between 1975 and 1979, were executed or died of starvation, disease or overworking, approximately 1.7 million people.
When in 1979, the Vietnamese invaded and toppled the government led by Pol Pot, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the border from Cambodia with Thailand.
There launched an insurgency that lasted until the last movement which surrendered in December 1998.
Like Pol Pot, Nuon Chea, Ieng Sary received guerrilla warfare from bases in the mountains and forests in Western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in anlong veng.
But in the 1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the UN to the first democratic elections in the country in 1993, large groups of combatants of the Khmer Rouge began to desert towards the government, culminating in the rendiciones of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea; Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the dangrek mountains nearby.
Died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while waiting for the process.
Without the support of its benefactors, the oldest combatants of the Khmer Rouge fell in absolute poverty which is common in rural Cambodia, and many are nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite officials of the Khmer Rouge continued with their local administrative posts in exchange for abandoning their weapons, the soldiers rasos remain poor and not qualified.
"These people have received few benefits then accountability," said Sok leang of the Center for justice and reconciliation, which offers public forums across Cambodia, even in anlong veng.
"They have built into the ideology of agrarian utopian regime."
"They were bred without any concept to do business."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge when I was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near anlong veng before engaging to life as a farmer of poor rice in 1998.
"life with the Khmer Rouge was good," she said.
"Ta Mok gave him to eat at all."
"But now the life is difficult because we have to autoabastecernos."
The current court of the Khmer Rouge has also caused concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, it is expected that the Court begins to prosecute Nuon Chea; Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng thirith, another former Minister of the Khmer Rouge.
The mandate of the Court is to prosecute the main leaders and those of greater responsibility for the crimes, but has not said whether it will cases of these four.
This is not done much to calm fears in anlong veng.
The recent media speculation has focused on im chaem, aged 64, who was a district chief in the province of banteay meanchey during Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told investigators the documentation centre of Cambodia, which had overseen the construction of the dam of trapeang thma, a project which thinks that have killed thousands of slave labour.
During a recent scandalous later, IM chaem came back from work in the camps to their home on pilotes of wood in a path of land on the outskirts of anlong veng.
When the sun fired long shadows on the parched grass, IM chaem refusal to talk about his past in the Khmer Rouge.
She said that if the court convened would not.
"Cambodia is peace and stable," she said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who desertó of the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability if the Court does more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," she said.
But the past is exactly what Cambodia must do to advance, said youk chhang, the documentation centre.
"The reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to connect the pieces broken," she said.
"It is our duty to bring these pieces broken so that we can understand."
The center was the first book of text approved by the government on the Khmer Rouge, called "history of Democratic Kampuchea," 75 pages.
It was distributed in anlong veng in June as an addition to book history of school of Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of anlong veng know few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the link of the city with the regime.
Touch valeak, 19, a student at the school in anlong veng, said that the new textbook helped the students to understand a significant part of their history.
But their parents reacted with skepticism when brought the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the book of text and the Court," she said.
"They have suspicions because they are not sure about the number of people who processed by the Court."
Such resistance has made the process of reconciliation is complex and difficult, said Sok leang.
But the public forums, the textbook and the Court are beginning to make an impact, she said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful charm.
In the dangrek mountains, a road with too many weeds and covered in plastic bags offal leads to a rectangle of black soot covered by a rusty tin ceiling.
The body of Pol Pot was burned here on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom sothea, 31, a seller of mobile phones to the edge of the road, said that he did not know much about the man who was cremated there.
"but he has a strong spirit and many people in the place to go rezarle," she said.
It was the birthday of nuom sothea, and later that day decided to walk up to the last rest of Pol Pot, which would leave a whole bunch of bananas mature hoping for good luck.
Belarus is giving up its stockpile of uranium qualified for armaments
In a stunning victory for the campaign of President Obama to protect the nuclear material around the world, the government of Belarus announced on Wednesday that will surrender its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement released after the Minister of Foreign Affairs Hillary Rodham Clinton met with the Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov, on the sidelines of a summit of security.
For years, the US Government had been trying to persuade Belarus that renounced its highly enriched uranium and it seemed that they had reached a point of no return last spring.
But American officials said the Washington Post did a couple of classified operations with Belarus in the last two months, to withdraw 84,82 kg of uranium for weapons as an installation of Belarusian investigations.
This paved the way for the agreement on Wednesday to remove the rest of the material, about 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity because of the confidentiality of the issue.
The agreement appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the Summit of nuclear safety in 47 nations chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And it was a good achievement securing the invitation of the former Soviet Republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I was fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the summit of nuclear safety in 2012."
"This shows that this process is working," said Ken luongo, President of the society for global security, a group that promotes nuclear safety.
Clinton said that the agreement is "a very important step and significant" given by Belarus.
In April 2009 Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide within the next four years.
Since then, the US government has helped to six countries to get rid of all its highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of the Summit of nuclear safety of Obama, the Belarusian President, Alexander Lukashenko, stated that the country never will not give up its uranium.
"We have maintained the highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what basically is qualified to uranium weapons) and the low-enriched uranium," said Lukashenko in that time.
"This is our raw material... we are not going to make dirty bombs, and we are not giving them to anyone."
"use it for research purposes, is everything."
However, Belarus moved to the United States a few months ago, indicating interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials said that the first task of removing uranium of Belarus, in October, was particularly difficult, because the material had been slightly irradiated.
Officials said that was loaded on a train travelled more than 2,000 km to a Russian facility to storage and disposal.
According to the officials, the second operation was completed on Monday and was made by plane.
The US government spent 13 billion dollars for the tasks, and most of the money is used to feed to Belarus the installation of investigations with uranium enrichment, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew bieniawski, an official of the Department of energy, which operates in the reduction of global threat, said that "this was coordinated and orchestrated with very careful to build confidence" that led to the agreement signed by Clinton.
The James Martin Center for nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus possessed at least 40 kilograms of uranium qualified for weapons, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will eliminate its stockpile by 2012, according to the joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly due to the repression gritty of Lukashenko of human rights.
But the statement on Wednesday suggested a potential thaw.
It said that "while it welcomes the progress on these issues of global security, the United States and Belarus recognised that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains a central issue to improve bilateral relations, and it is essential for the progress of the country and its citizens."
The Spanish Government not lodged objections to the CIA flights
The Spanish Government not lodged objections to the CIA flights with prisoners Taliban and al-Qaeda with the direction of Guantánamo by Spanish territory, according to said in a telegram to the US ambassador in Madrid.
So they reflect the documents leaked (cables) by WikiLeaks in the newspaper the country, where the then senior vice-chairman of the government, María Teresa Fernández de la Vega, demanded that the Spanish executive was reported to "be able to show that exercising appropriate monitoring on foreign aircraft that are in Spain."
In June 2006, following a report by the Council of Europe in which it accused of complicity in practices contrary to human rights in a dozen countries, including Spain, there was a meeting between the former American Ambassador Eduardo Aguirre and Fernandez de la Vega.
The Vice-President admitted that the report of the Council "had picked up the Zapatero government outside game" and insisted that Spain had nothing to hide in this matter.
"from the Vega stressed that Spain has no objections to the intelligence flights through Spanish territory."
"They just want to be informed" to avoid becoming "burnt unprepared," Aguirre described in a cable.
The then head of Foreign Affairs, Miguel Ángel Moratinos, pointed out to the Ambassador that the Spanish executive "wanted to give this issue the profile low as possible, although, to be in the hands of judges, the government had a limited ability to influence."
For its part, in January 2007, the prosecutor Vicente Gonzalez conveyed to the embassy that she would not seek to block the initiative of the judge of asking for the declassification of documents from the national intelligence centre (CNI) and the Ministry of Defence on the CIA flights.
"these reports do not contain any incriminatorio nor any sensitive information," said the embassy after speaking with the prosecutor.
However, the US reflected his concern about the "apparent coordination between the Spanish judge and prosecutors Germans," rather than by the information desclasificada the CNI or the Ministry of Defence.
"This coordination among independent researchers will complicate our efforts to handle the case quietly between governments," laments Aguirre.
In March 2007 in a lunch meeting between the Ambassador of the US and the Interior Minister, Alfredo Pérez Rubalcaba, he commented that "although the Spanish judges are rabiosamente jealous of their independence and will do what they themselves consider appropriate," he had instructed his employees to avoid comments of inflamada rhetoric, in an attempt to lower the temperature ."
The Ambassador also expresses its concern about action by the PP in this matter.
"despite its general orientation pro-American, our experience suggests that the PP will not hesitate to capitalize on any indication that the Zapatero government tolerated or deliberately ignored US actions that could be construed as possible violations of human rights, even if these revelations have negative consequences for the US government," says.
