Network bull succeeds in Formula 1 with a secret weapon of Siemens
A software engineers improvements in cars in real time.
Since network bull burst into the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and with success.
In a prime time nobody took into consideration the options of a escudería new arrival and, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, last November, in the final straight championship all gambled by the triumph of the Ferrari of Fernando Alonso.
Without detracting from the skill as pilot of the eventual champion, German Sebastian vettel, nor the ability of the Renault engine to drive his car in the world of Formula 1 has become a legend "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of network bull into a winning team.
This is in fact a powerful software simulation of processes that the German put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from the car racing.
So-called plm, this powerful computer instrument has been used to design line of manufacturing plants throughout the world, power plants, high precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce, faithfully simulating the product or process before building it so real, avoiding the gaps and unnecessary expenditure.
Plm facilitated the development of the cameras, the Sukhoi planes or cars more famous slew of Nissan.
Siegfried russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains that the use of this instrument in its computer factory Formula 1 has allowed network bull design and lead to "in a few hours, almost in real time," modifications, changes and improvements that are for the careers and in testing.
Russwurm explains that the escuderías in 1992 had an average of 10 points in his team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements in vehicles during each season.
In the team of network bull at work 180 young professionals of highly qualified, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyse and cast all kinds of changes in the bólidos.
The manager explained that the Siemens plm software is capable of analysing and improve all the elements of the bólidos network bull except the engine, which is full responsibility for Renault.
Amending the materials, the fuel, the aircrafts and elements of security.
The changes can be implemented in the virtual reality of the simulador to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced systems of production using lasers and autoclaves of high technology.
As only limitation of this lunacy of technological upgrading is the figure of 40 million dollars that each team of Formula 1 can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Network bull has mounted the factory of high technology to design and produce their bólidos in a village some 50 miles from London.
These two buildings in which are restricted visits, especially for journalists.
All events there is considered "top secret."
The template for this task at 580 people, including their two pilots, the champion vettel and mark webber.
The hero of the Formula 1 grid bull, without doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian vetell.
Between the huge technological resources that the mark of energy drinks has put at the service of their participation in the channels, are hiding other actors whose competition is invaluable and zero visibility.
The head of technology at the factory, Steve nevey, says that five years ago you could say that the progress of R [amp] D in cars of carts gave the 50% of the victories and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and technology amount 85% of success, while the pilots provide 15% of the value added.
Nevey recognizes that vettel and webber will never be replaced by the technology because "gladiators" are unpredictable.
