The Pakistani nuclear program generates great concern in the US
Islamabad produces nuclear weapons into "a faster rate than any other country."
Leaks of WikiLeaks confirms the links between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the United States Embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department, filtered by the portal WikiLeaks confirms the huge concerns that causes in Washington, the Pakistani nuclear program.
Apart from the enlightening and juicy details that offer on the content of the talks and the thoughts of representatives accredited American diplomats in Islamabad, the documents show that cooperation between both countries in terms of nuclear safety, instead of in, "modernization," and that the volatile Asian country produces nuclear weapons' at a faster rate than any other country in the world ."
The particularity of the Pakistani nuclear program - that weapons are not ensambladas but remain in storage for components to hinder its destruction in case of ataque-- constitutes one of the main reasons of devotion in Washington.
It lists the Ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, in a previous report to the visit of the then national security adviser, James Jones: "the proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumoreada dispersion of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of transport of nuclear materials."
The high number of people involved in the nuclear arsenals and in the programmes of missiles is viewed, not only for America, but also for Russia, as proliferante and reason to keep the guard.
"Pakistan has had to recruit staff with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the fall in levels of education and culture, the extremist organisations have more opportunities to recruit people who work in the nuclear programs and missiles," said the expert Yuri Korolev, the Russian Foreign Ministry, in a meeting with their American counterparts.
The latest of the documents leaked by the portal of Julian Assange is decreasing cooperation between America and Pakistan in issues of nuclear proliferation and the high rate of Pakistani nuclear weapons production.
A Member of the embassy in May, as a "frustrating" communication with Pakistan, argues: "transparency is often non-existent; the offers of assistance are unanswered or are excluded."
In another message, Peter lavoy, an official of the national intelligence for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic disaster, Pakistan has nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world."
The Ambassador Patterson also calls on Washington, during a visit by the head of the army, General Ashfaq Kayani, who left "very clear" that the person responsible, "the army of Pakistan must end with the tacit support to terrorist groups."
The hunting of the head of WikiLeaks
Obama appointed a senior officer of the fight against terrorism to prevent further occurrences.
Interpol issued a red alert in order to monitor movements and locate where Assange.
Everything to do with WikiLeaks and its founder, Julian Assange, form a complicated maze where it is difficult to be absolutely certain about the facts.
Interpol yesterday issued a "red alert" to "find and follow the movements" of Assange.
However, this is not an arrest warrant.
Moreover, it is not new, but dating from 20 November.
And it has to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million diplomatic documents of America but with accusations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer of the Creator of WikiLeaks, mark Stephens, ensures that "the police know where and how to contact Mr Assange."
It was the day 20 when the international police task force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but not revealed yesterday, after receiving permission from the authorities of that country.
So, the 188 countries of Interpol have information to identify or trace Assange "with a view to its provisional arrest and extradition."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of a man hit by a red alert, many of the Member States, as he explained the organization, considered the so-called network notice the way for an arrest -- will be the Spanish national police, particularly if they have a bilateral agreement on extradition, as is the case of Sweden and England, where it is believed that is Assange.
The movement has outraged lawyers of Assange, yesterday published a letter to the effect that the founder of WikiLeaks, 39, has been prepared to respond by video link to the questions of the Swedish authorities.
They also recall that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden of the prosecutor in his case, to compare with the mythical pavlovich lavrentiy Beria, the head of security of Stalin.
"This is a hunt, not a legal persecution," the letter.
While the world we seek - and from Australia his mother defends the innocence of their hijo-- Assange fate remains unknown, but not silent.
