"I think that we can achieve an agreement at any time on this, and then we can plan the sequence of the rest," he said.
The leader of the democratic majority in the Senate, Harry Reid, announced on Tuesday to urge a "vote of shutting down debate" for the dream act, for which the initiative for legalising undocumented students could be voted on starting next Thursday in the Senate, though it is more likely next week.
The senatorial version of the dream act or law of the American dream would legalise some 800 000 young people who entered the United States before the age of 16 years, have remained in the country the past five years and joined an institution of higher education or the military.
But supporters needed 60 votes to approve the initiative, by which require the involvement of a handful of Republicans, even as the party organizations involved lobbying to ensure the adoption of the law.
The Democrats, the majority of which supports the dream act, have 58 seats.
But at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of nebraska, have said they will vote against, and only a Republican has voiced support for the law, Richard place of Indiana.
Therefore, the supporters of the dream act require join several Republicans if other Democrats decided to back the initiative.
Among the Republicans are the most cortejados senadoras from Maine, Olympia snowe and Susan Collins, as well as the outgoing Senator George lemieux, of Florida, who completed the term of Senator Mel Martinez.
Other Republicans who supported in the past the dream act are orrin hatch of Utah, and Kay Bailey Hutchinson, of Texas, but they have declared that they support it on another occasion.
Another Republican who supported John McCain, has defined its position at the moment.
Although the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree that the dream act is facing the biggest obstacles in the Senate.
