The US is changing rules for visa
People have to go to the toilet to applicants of visa before his interview in the consular section; the cost will be less and as well as the time.
As from 10 January 2011 will change the procedure for dealing with a visa in the United States Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to go to the toilet to applicants of visa (JSA) before his interview in the consular section.
The staff of the JSA will take the biometric information of the applicant, which will be reviewed by the consular section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for the candidates, including:
The total cost of the visa will be less, because it will not be necessary to make a down payment to make the appointment, another payment to process the application of visa and another for the courier Service delivered the document.
The candidate will only make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate to remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for cases of visas with the request (including visas for seasonal workers) and $390 for visas of traders and investors.
People who want to renew his visa will not have to go through an interview with a consular official, but that only convene the JSA closer where will present their documents and they will take their fingerprints.
Because the biometric information will be taken in the JSA, applicants requiring a second quotation to be interviewed in the consular section, will remain in this less time than in the past.
Equally, those who apply for visa from the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and new laredo no longer pay the extra charge of $26.
For additional information about the new procedure to apply for visa, visit the following web site http: / / mexico.usembassy.gov / bulletins / sp101201 _ visas-faqs.html
NASA announced finding life extraterrestre
The US space agency quoted in the press for tomorrow present a discovery which will impact on the search for living beings in space.
The administration for the national aeronautics and space (NASA) of the United States will be released tomorrow, Thursday, a discovery astrobiológico, that could prove the theory that there is life extraterrestre.
The findings will be presented at a press conference Thursday at 1 p.m. in the NASA headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiología, described as the science of the origin, evolution, and future of life in the universe.
To quote the press, NASA that will present "a discovery which will impact on the search for life extraterrestre," which triggered speculation of experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that there are creatures to the couple our and hostile environments that they thought uninhabitable, and which might put on the table the possibility of becoming intelligent beings as humans if they improve the conditions in which they live.
Apparently this was a microbe that was found at the bottom of the monkey lake in the yosemite national park, California, where he lives in an environment that was thought too poisonous to any form of life, as the Lake is rich in arsenic.
Somehow, the creature uses arsenic as a way to survive and this capability increases the possibility that similar life could exist on other planets, which do not have our friendly atmosphere.
According to astrobiólogos, whether these bodies use arsenic in their metabolism, it will demonstrate that "there is another way of life, a second way of life, other than we know."
The Space Agency will know the true extent of the findings in a press conference Thursday morning.
In the conference will take the geobióloga pamela Conrad, who is investigating the possibility of life on Mars; and biologist Steven benner, one of the scientists who study titan may (the largest moon of Saturn), under the prospect of their chemistry is similar to that of earth.
