"maybe the political leaders are characterised by an inferiority complex almost inherent to the Canadians to tackling the daily domestic issues, rather than leave the choice to the United States (like during the campaign about free trade in 1988)," writes.
Consequently, it concludes, the United States are "the proverbial elephant in this election: everywhere, but potentially too dangerous to talk about it."
The Ambassador has even more problems in understanding this "deafening silence" because the two countries have a strong political and economic relations.
"of course, is the ability of a candidate, a party and, even more, the head of a party to manage these essential relations should be a key factor in which should think the electorate to vote."
You can observe this sense of importance also cable sent on 22 January 2009 by Terry breese, the chargé d " affaires in Ottawa, to prepare President Barack Obama for his first visit to Ottawa.
"her trip will help to ensure the survival of the government during the vote of confidence at the beginning of February on the federal budget, through which Canada will for the first time in the last decade due to a recovery plan for between 30 000 and 40 000 million dollars," writes Mr breese.
There are no mentions that the government had to extend the Parliament before Christmas to avoid that replaced the coalition and the opposition parties condicionaban his survival to the quality of the proposed recovery plan.
Another communication of January 2008 signed by Ambassador wilkins alert to Washington about the image increasingly negative convey the drama series broadcast in the CBC of United States.
The Ambassador expressed concern the issue of border, little mosque on the prairie, intelligence and H2O, which are heavy-handed references to Maher Arar, "no-fly-list" or even to the persecution to which the CIA conducts energetic interrogations.
